    pearls: ["The Lachman test is the MOST SENSITIVE test for ACL tear (87% sensitivity) -- always perform at 20-30 degrees of flexion (not 90 degrees like the anterior drawer) because hamstring relaxation at this angle reduces guarding and false negatives","McMurray test: external rotation tests the MEDIAL meniscus; internal rotation tests the LATERAL meniscus -- remember 'EMIA' (External rotation = Medial meniscus; Internal rotation = Lateral meniscus... well, 'opposite' is the key)","A hot, swollen, monoarticular joint with fever is SEPTIC ARTHRITIS until proven otherwise -- aspiration with synovial fluid analysis (WBC >50,000, >75% PMNs) and Gram stain/culture is mandatory before treatment; delay in surgical washout increases morbidity; Staphylococcus aureus is the most common organism","Trendelenburg sign: when standing on the AFFECTED leg, the CONTRALATERAL pelvis drops because the ipsilateral gluteus medius is too weak to stabilize the pelvis; indicates gluteus medius dysfunction from L5 radiculopathy, hip OA, or superior gluteal nerve injury","FABER test (Patrick test) stresses both the HIP joint and the SACROILIAC joint: groin pain = hip pathology; posterior (SI) pain = sacroiliac pathology; document which pain is produced for accurate diagnosis","The 'drop arm test' is pathognomonic for a COMPLETE rotator cuff tear: the patient cannot slowly lower the arm from 90 degrees of abduction (the arm drops to the side) because the supraspinatus cannot eccentrically control descent"],
